It's the one game romance where there's also an actual point to it. Ahnassi is the only romance character who ever actually gave me something. Sure, you can rob the vault without her, but she turns you towards it. Without her, you might have never thought about it.

It's honestly pretty rare for a game romantic option to not be a passive factor, gameplay wise. They're often questgivers, but the dynamic there is that you are winning their favor, while Ahnassi is also trying to win yours. I'd like to see that sort of thing more in games like this. Woo the countess, and you get a sick castle. Fuck the wizard, and she involves you in a world-altering ritual. A proper narrative needs to be married to consequences in the world, and an NPC that simply gets a few more voice lines and a cutscene doesn't cut it.

>>19791841

Realtalk, here. Especially when you're starting out, every prompt you come up with is going to be - or at least feel like - the next epic to rival the Odyssey. A lot of this is because you've not had practice thinking through a plot in the detail that it takes to get a story down. As you get more familiar with taking stories out of the comfy, cozy, enticingly nebulous, cradle of your mind, and into the cold, harsh, material, world of reality land, you'll get way better at coming up with stories that fit the scope you want to write.

Additionally, you are ALWAYS going to feel super motivated to write something riiiiight up to the point where you go to start putting fingers to keyboard. I know. It happens to me damn near every time I try to write something (that I really only get to do so in passing, or late at night does not help. YAAAAY real life obligations!) Because of this, you will need to:
a.) Exercise discipline and just grind it out for the first few things you write
b.) Drastically re-scope/de-scope your story (or if, like me, you're too goddamn hardheaded to do so) be ready to have something take a long-ass time.

If you start with a plot or theme that you're not really married to, you'll be much better equipped to get in, get out, and get on with your writing.

Protip: If you're writing something that might or might not get continued past the first update, HAVE YOUR DESERT FIRST!!!

...at least that's what this rank amateur decided to do.

- Jack Dawe

One small input, if I may, on the digitigrade feets. If you're going to go with them, take a look at some pictures of animals and how their limbs work. The trick, more than anything, is to mix it up.

If there's just two characters slinging dialogue, you can always just double space and cut loose. The readers will have no trouble following along, and they generally do a good job of incorporating inflection if your dialogue is written naturally enough. Just have characters call each other out by name every now and again (or by their pet names) so it's easier to follow who's saying what.

If your characters are doing shit while they're talking, you can run your writing kinda like D&D notes, where you describe the person's actions in the same block as their speech. You can also use X/Y Said to clarify when one person is talking and someone else is doing something. It reads way more naturally than it sounds.

If you've got a scene where the characters words and intentions don't align naturally (sarcasm, allusion, double entendre, etc.) you can expound upon "He said/ she said" to clarify tone. E.G.

At the end of the day, there's no hard and fast rule with it. Have fun playing with character interaction, and at least someone will have fun reading said interaction.

E.G. Short, because char. limits:

>"So, how'd it go, then, Crash?!" chided Elsa, the pause letting his nickname play double duty in the question."
>"Fuck!" Crash half gasped, half shouted.
>"Things were going great until dinner, then I had to go and put my foot in my mouth." He leaned in over the bar, cash in hand, to lure the bartender over.
>"I didn't think you were that flexible"
>"You're a riot, Els'..." Getting the attention of a bartender, he pointed at the tap he wanted, then held a hand about a foot above the bar, signing that he wanted a tall.
>"Okay, so... Dinner... Go on."
>*Sigh* "Well, we were discussing what we were going to get to eat, and Sherry - "
>"Like the wine?"
>"Yes! Like the wine! The fuck does it matter?!"
>"Jeeze! Sorry, go on..." Elsa chided, putting her hands in mock self defense.

Oliver_FART here.

Most of your tags should be "says/said", as adding a modifier/adjective afterwards becomes noticeable and tiresome. Save that for when you're being deliberate or you have something you want to convey.

>"I really like pizza," he says
>"I really like pizza," he quipped, mulling over the empty boxes with a sad face

Just use say/said. Everything else is sparing.

Seconding Cordwainer Smith.

He was a really strange and unique author of American science fiction in the mid 20th Century.

His real name was Paul Linebarger. He served in US Army Intelligence during WWII and was one of the people who created the Psychological Warfare department. He lived in China for decades on and off before the Revolution. Sun Yat-Sen was his godfather.

His prose and authorial voice were unique and I have never seen anyone able to imitate it convincingly for more than a few sentences, and I know people who make a hobby of imitating writing styles. And his subject matter was heavily influenced by Chinese and Russian folklore, among other things.

He wrote stories set thousands and thousands of years in the future, with magical, almost godlike technology as part of the backdrop--which made the stories feel as much like fantasy as like science fiction--and wrote stories about, among other things, cats.

In "The Game of Rat and Dragon" he wrote of a future of faster-than-light starships, in which human pilots had to be teamed with trained cats to do psychic battle against unimaginable eldritch abominations that lived in the empty places between the stars and between dimensions.

In "The Ballad of Lost C'Mell," he wrote a story of a human lost on an Earth inhabited mostly by "Underpeople," genetically engineered slaves of mixed human and animal stock who are horribly oppressed by the government, and the human falls in love with a catgirl named C'Mell.

I am pretty sure he liked cats.

He died in 1966. He was only fifty-three years old.

Here, have a link for some free ebooks of stories he wrote.

http://cordwainer-smith.com/blog/you-can-read-several-cordwainer-smith-science-fiction-stories-online-free.html
